  "prompt": "Is there a consensus that money laundering is against the law?",
  "response": "Yes, there is a strong global consensus that money laundering is against the law. Money laundering involves disguising the origins of illegally obtained money, typically by transferring it through legitimate businesses or financial systems to make it appear as though it comes from legal sources. This practice is universally condemned because it facilitates criminal activities such as drug trafficking, terrorism, corruption, and fraud.\n\nMost countries have enacted laws and regulations to combat money laundering. For example:\n\n1. **United States**: The Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) and the USA PATRIOT Act include provisions to detect and prevent money laundering.\n2. **European Union**: The EU has implemented several Anti-Money Laundering Directives (AMLD) to harmonize and strengthen anti-money laundering (AML) measures across member states.\n3. **Global Standards**: The Financial Action Task Force (FATF), an intergovernmental organization, sets international standards for combating money laundering and terrorist financing. Over 200 countries and jurisdictions have committed to implementing FATF recommendations.\n\nInternational cooperation and enforcement agencies, such as INTERPOL and the United Nations, also work to combat money laundering globally. Penalties for money laundering can be severe, including hefty fines, asset forfeiture, and imprisonment.\n\nIn summary, money laundering is widely recognized as illegal and is actively targeted by laws and regulations worldwide.",
